The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, April 28, 2004 				 IPCL net profit inches up 10% 
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 				 	 Ambani: More to do																								Mumbai, April 27: Indian Petrochemicals Corporation Ltd (IPCL) has posted a modest 10 per cent growth in fourth-quarter profit at Rs 99 crore as compared with Rs 90 crore in the corresponding previous period.																								While gross turnover rose to Rs 3,973 crore (Rs 2,766 crore), the net turnover (net of inter-divisional transfers and excise duty) jumped to Rs 2,620 crore (Rs 1,373 crore), a hefty growth of 91 per cent. Thus it was the higher provision for deferred tax at Rs 56 crore (Rs 2 crore) that resulted in IPCL posting a modest growth in its bottomline.																								Fiscal 2003-04 marked the completion of the first year of IPCLs operations under the Reliance management. The initiatives introduced to increase capacity utilisation, reduce operating costs and enhance overall productivity and efficiency have resulted in improved financial and operating performance, chairman Mukesh Ambani said.																								Anil Ambani was appointed vice-chairman of IPCL today. He was already a director on the board. He is currently vice-chairman and managing director of Reliance Industries and chairman of Reliance Energy.																								In 2003-04, the gross turnover of IPCL rose 36 per cent at Rs 13,541 crore against Rs 9,921 crore in the year-ago period. Net profit increased 34 per cent to Rs 273 crore against Rs 204 crore.																								While production volumes during the year touched 4.6 million tonnes  an increase of 5 per cent  the operating margin for the year was marginally lower at 10.7 per cent due to higher input costs on account of reduced availability of gas.																								IPCL said production volumes of polypropylene, polyethylene and poly vinyl chloride increased 2.4 per cent to over 9.89 lakh tonnes in the year. 																								Domestic demand for polymers increased 12 per cent in 2003-04, reflecting the general improvement in the economy.																								During the year, the company produced 8.35 lakh tonnes of ethylene, an increase of 2 per cent while PP production was at 2.97 lakh tonnes.Reliance Capital																								Reliance Capital has posted a 13.9 per cent rise in its consoliated net profit at Rs 172.64 crore in 2003-04 against Rs 151.5 crore in 2002-03. The board has recommended a dividend of 29 per cent on shares of Rs 10 each.																								Consolidated total income in 2003-04 decreased to Rs 458 crore from Rs 533.5 crore in the previous fiscal. On a standalone basis, the company posted a net profit of Rs 105.7 crore in 2003-04 against Rs 102.6 crore in the previous fiscal. 
